# Reelattice git push checklist

Before **committing and pushing** to `main` (or any shared branch), always review whether the Changelog tab needs an update — even for small or minor changes.

## When to update

Update `src/lib/changelog.ts` if the push includes anything a user might care about:

- New UI, changed workflows, fixes they would notice
- Website, download, legal, or privacy changes
- Import, playback, export, Cases, Settings, or Help behavior
- Performance or reliability improvements users would feel

Skip changelog-only noise: internal refactors, CI/workflows, dev tooling, `.gitignore`, docs for developers only.

## How to write entries

- Add bullets to the **current version** entry if still shipping under that release, **or** add a new top entry when cutting a new version (see `reelattice-release.mdc`).
- Write for end users in the Help/Changelog voice — what changed and why it matters, not file names or PR titles.
- One clear bullet per user-visible change; group tiny related tweaks into one bullet.
- Date format matches existing entries (`June 2026`).

## Before push

1. `git diff` — list user-visible changes since the last changelog update.
2. Update `src/lib/changelog.ts` when needed.
3. If update flow or Changelog tab copy changed, skim `src/components/changelog-view.tsx` and `src/components/help-view.tsx`.
4. Commit changelog with the related changes (same commit or clearly linked).

Do not push user-facing work without a changelog entry when users would benefit from knowing.
